===Etymology===
From Old Russian '''цьсарь''' < O.C.S. '''{{Unicode|цѣсарь}}''' < Gothic '''kaisar''' (emperor) < Greek '''{{IPAchar|καῖσαρ}}''' < Latin '''[[Caesar]]'''.

===Noun===
'''царь''' (tsar’) ''m'', цари (tsarí) ''pl''

#[[czar]], Russian [[emperor]]
#[[king]]
#:*царь [[зверь|зверей]] (tsar’ zveréj) — ''king of beasts''
#:*царь [[и]] [[бог]] (tsar’ i boχ) — ''God Almighty''
#:*царь [[небесный]] (tsar’ nebésnyj) — ''Heavenly Father''
#:*царь царей (tsar’ tsaréj) — ''King of kings''
#:*[[при]] царе Горохе (pri tsaré Goróχe) — ''in the year dot; a very long time ago; since the beginning''
#:*[[Он]] [[без]] царя [[в]] [[голова|голове]]! (on bez tsarjá v golové) — ''He’s stupid!''

